  "slug": "filling-a-window-board-gap",
  "title": "Filling a window-board gap",
  "subtitle": "Seal the joint between window board and plaster with filler and caulk",
  "excerpt": "How to fill and seal the gap that opens between a window board and the surrounding plaster: backing the deep gap with expanding foam, applying filler to level the surface, finishing with a flexible caulk bead, and painting over.",
  "type": "PATTERN",
  "sourceNotes": "Standard UK decorating practice. Collins Complete DIY Manual.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The gap that opens between a window board and the surrounding plaster is one of the most common finishing faults in a redecorated room. It appears because the timber window board moves seasonally while the plaster does not. A rigid filler cracks when the movement recurs; the correct fill is a shallow rigid filler layer for appearance, sealed with a flexible ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "caulk",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpe8rbpz0000pcv4p7ml98iv"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " bead at the interface.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "What you'll need",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Flexible decorator's caulk.",
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "text": " Overpaintable acrylic sealant. Available in 300 ml cartridges; a standard caulking gun accepts the cartridge. Sold as interior filler-caulk or flexible gap filler at builders' merchants.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Lightweight filler.",
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "text": " For filling any deep section of the gap before the caulk coat.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "50 mm and 100 mm filling knives.",
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Sanding block, 120-grit.",
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Expanding PU foam.",
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "text": " For any gap deeper than 10 mm that would take excessive filler to fill solid.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Preparing the gap",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Step 1, clean out the gap. ",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": "Remove any old filler, caulk, or paint that has bridged the gap by picking and cutting it clear. Vacuum out the dust. A clean gap bonds better than a packed one.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Step 2, back-fill deep gaps. ",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": "If the gap is deeper than 10 mm, squeeze a small amount of expanding PU foam into the void (not more than a quarter fill; it expands to several times its wet volume). Allow to cure, then slice back flush with a craft knife.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Filling and caulking",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Step 3, apply filler for surface continuity. ",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": "If the gap is visible as a step between the window board and the plaster, apply lightweight filler to the plaster side only, feathering it out from the board edge. Do not pack filler into the joint itself. Allow to dry and sand flush.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Step 4, apply the caulk. ",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": "Gun a small bead of flexible caulk into the joint between the window board and the plaster. Run a wet finger along the bead to press it into the joint and leave a neat, slightly concave profile. Wipe away any excess with a damp cloth. Allow to skin fully (at minimum 2 hours) before painting.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Painting",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Once the caulk is fully cured (24 hours), it can be overpainted with standard emulsion or gloss. Caulk applied to unpainted surfaces needs painting; it yellows and shrinks slightly if left exposed.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Troubleshooter",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "troubleshooterRow",
            "attrs": {
              "fix": "Cut out the old caulk, back-fill the void with backer rod (a foam cylinder that fills the gap and gives the caulk a suitable depth), then apply a fresh caulk bead over the backer rod.",
              "cause": "Too much caulk was applied in a single bead, or the gap is too wide for caulk alone.",
              "symptom": "Caulk cracks the following winter"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "troubleshooterRow",
            "attrs": {
              "fix": "Remove all rigid filler from the joint. Replace with flexible caulk only.",
              "cause": "The window board is moving; rigid filler cannot flex with it.",
              "symptom": "Rigid filler in the joint is cracking repeatedly"
            }
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
